===Etymology 1===
* First attested around 1200.
* {{sense|residence}} First attested in 1576.
* From {{etyl|ang}} {{term|abad|lang=ang}}, {{term|abod||a stay, delay, continuance|lang=ang}}, from {{term|abidan|ābīdan|to abide|lang=ang}}.
* See ''[[abide]]''. For the change of vowel, compare ''abode'', imp. of ''abide''.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{obsolete}} Act of [[waiting]]; delay.
#* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', III.viii:
#*: Vpon his Courser set the louely lode, / And with her fled away without '''abode'''.
# {{uncommon|_|outside fixed expressions}} Stay or [[continuance]] in a place; [[sojourn]].
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|Henry Fielding}}
#*: He waxeth at your '''abode''' here. 
# {{formal}} A residence, [[dwelling]] or [[habitation]].
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|William Wordsworth}}
#*: Come, let me lead you to our poore '''abode'''.

